main event: A group of four silver objects, each the size of a pinhead, were observed passing across the sky from west to southwest in Colorado Springs in 1936.
interesting points: The objects were traveling in formation, close together, as a cluster.
The objects were only observed for a brief duration of five seconds.
The report concludes that the sighting was likely a group of meteors.
This was a ground-radar observation reported by a civilian source.
No photographs were included in the Project 10073 record card.
sighted object: four silver objects, each the size of a pinhead
